A and B can be physically interacting but not necessarily. Immediately upstream means there are no intermediate entity between A and B.

Subject: definition
Value: <2012-04-05: Barry SmithThe official OBI definition, explaining the meaning of a class or property: 'Shall be Aristotelian, formalized and normalized. Can be augmented with colloquial definitions' is terrible.Can you fix to something like:A statement of necessary and sufficient conditions explaining the meaning of an expression referring to a class or property.Alan RuttenbergYour proposed definition is a reasonable candidate, except that it is very common that necessary and sufficient conditions are not given. Mostly they are necessary, occasionally they are necessary and sufficient or just sufficient. Often they use terms that are not themselves defined and so they effectively can't be evaluated by those criteria. On the specifics of the proposed definition:We don't have definitions of 'meaning' or 'expression' or 'property'. For 'reference' in the intended sense I think we use the term 'denotation'. For 'expression', I think we you mean symbol, or identifier. For 'meaning' it differs for class and property. For class we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine whether an entity is instance of the class, or not. For property we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine, given a pair of potential relata, whether the assertion that the relation holds is true. The 'intended reader' part suggests that we also specify who, we expect, would be able to understand the definition, and also generalizes over human and computer reader to include textual and logical definition. Personally, I am more comfortable weakening definition to documentation, with instructions as to what is desirable. We also have the outstanding issue of how to aim different definitions to different audiences. A clinical audience reading chebi wants a different sort of definition documentation/definition from a chemistry trained audience, and similarly there is a need for a definition that is adequate for an ontologist to work with. @en>

Value: x actively participates in y if and only if x participates in y and x realizes some active role

Subject: obsolete has active participant
Value: x has participant y if and only if x realizes some active role that inheres in y

Subject: surrounded by
Value: x surrounded_by y if and only if (1) x is adjacent to y and for every region r that is adjacent to x, r overlaps y (2) the shared boundary between x and y occupies the majority of the outermost boundary of x

Subject: surrounded by
Value: <x surrounded_by y iff: x is adjacent to y and for every region r adjacent to x, r overlaps y>

Subject: adjacent_to
Value: x adjacent to y if and only if x and y share a boundary.

Subject: adjacent_to
Value: <x adjacent_to y iff: x and y share a boundary>

Subject: starts with
Value: <x starts with y if and only if x has part y and the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: (y) = (x)  (y) < (x), where  is a function that maps a process to a start point, and  is a function that maps a process to an end point.>

Subject: develops from part of
Value: x develops from part of y if and only if there exists some z such that x develops from z and z is part of y

Subject: develops_in
Value: x develops_in y if x is located in y whilst x is developing

Subject: ends with
Value: <x ends with y if and only if x has part y and the time point at which x ends is equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: (y) > (x)  (y) = (x), where  is a function that maps a process to a start point, and  is a function that maps a process to an end point.>

Subject: has start location
Value: x 'has starts location' y if and only if there exists some process z such that x 'starts with' z and z 'occurs in' y

Subject: has end location
Value: x 'has end location' y if and only if there exists some process z such that x 'ends with' z and z 'occurs in' y

Subject: has input
has output
Value: p has output c iff c is a participant in p, c is present at the end of p, and c is not present at the beginning of p.

Subject: has developmental contribution from
Value: x has developmental contribution from y iff x has some part z such that z develops from y@en

Subject: developmentally contributes to
Value: inverse of has developmental contribution from

Subject: developmentally_induced_by
Value: <t1 developmentally_induced_by t2 if there is a process of organ induction (GO:0001759) with t1 and t2 as interacting participants. t2 causes t1 to change its fate from a precursor tissue type T to T', where T' develops_from T.>

Subject: developmentally_induced_by
Value: <t1 induced_by t2 if there is a process of developmental induction (GO:0031128) with t1 and t2 as interacting participants. t2 causes t1 to change its fate from a precursor anatomical structure type T to T', where T' develops_from T>

Subject: acts upstream of
Value: c acts upstream of p if and only if c enables some f that is involved in p' and p' occurs chronologically before p, is not part of p, and affects the execution of p. c is a material entity and f, p, p' are processes.

Subject: acts upstream of or within
Value: c acts upstream of or within p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of or within p. c is a material entity and p is an process.

Subject: developmentally replaces
Value: x developmentally replaces y if and only if there is some developmental process that causes x to move or to cease to exist, and for the site that was occupied by x to become occupied by y, where y either comes into existence in this site or moves to this site from somewhere else

Subject: results in developmental progression of
Value: p results in the developmental progression of s iff p is a developmental process and s is an anatomical structure and p causes s to undergo a change in state at some point along its natural developmental cycle (this cycle starts with its formation, through the mature structure, and ends with its loss).

Subject: has habitat
Value: <x 'has habitat' y if and only if: x is an organism, y is a habitat, and y can sustain and allow the growth of a population of xs.>

Subject: inheres in part of
Value: q inheres in part of w if and only if there exists some p such that q inheres in p and p part of w.

Subject: part of structure that is capable of
Value: this relation holds between c and p when c is part of some c', and c' is capable of p.

Subject: involved in
Value: c involved_in p if and only if c enables some process p', and p' is part of p

Subject: member of
Value: is member of is a mereological relation between a item and a collection.

Subject: has member
Value: has member is a mereological relation between a collection and an item.

Subject: attaches_to
Value: a is attached to b if and only if a and b are discrete objects or object parts, and there are physical connections between a and b such that a force pulling a will move b, or a force pulling b will move a

Subject: has muscle origin
Value: m has_muscle_origin s iff m is attached_to s, and it is the case that when m contracts, s does not move. The site of the origin tends to be more proximal and have greater mass than what the other end attaches to.@en

Subject: has muscle origin
Value: m has_muscle_origin s iff m is attaches_to s, and it is the case that when m contracts, s does not move. The site of the origin tends to be more proximal and have greater mass than what the other end attaches to.

Subject: has_muscle_insertion
Value: m has_muscle_insertion s iff m is attaches_to s, and it is the case that when m contracts, s moves. Insertions are usually connections of muscle via tendon to bone.

Subject: has_muscle_insertion
Value: m has_muscle_insertion s iff m is attaches_to s, and it is the case that when m contracts, s moves. Insertions are usually connections of muscle via tendon to bone.@en

Subject: tributary_of
Value: x tributary_of y if and only if x a channel for the flow of a substance into y, where y is larger than x. If x and y are hydrographic features, then y is the main stem of a river, or a lake or bay, but not the sea or ocean. If x and y are anatomical, then y is a vein.

Subject: spatially coextensive with
Value: x spatially_coextensive_with y if and inly if x and y have the same location

Subject: branching_part_of
Value: x is a branching part of y if and only if x is part of y and x is connected directly or indirectly to the main stem of y

Subject: has developmental potential involving
Value: x has developmental potential involving y iff x is capable of a developmental process with output y. y may be the successor of x, or may be a different structure in the vicinity (as for example in the case of developmental induction).@en

Subject: has potential to developmentally contribute to
Value: x has potential to developmentrally contribute to y iff x developmentally contributes to y or x is capable of developmentally contributing to y

Subject: has potential to developmentally contribute to
Value: x has potential to developmentrally contribute to y iff x developmentally contributes to y or x is capable of developmentally contributing to y@en

Subject: has potential to developmentally induce
Value: x has potential to developmentally induce y iff x developmentally induces y or x is capable of developmentally inducing y@en

Subject: has potential to develop into
Value: x has the potential to develop into y iff x develops into y or if x is capable of developing into y

Subject: has potential to develop into
Value: x has the potential to develop into y iff x develops into y or if x is capable of developing into y@en

Subject: has potential to directly develop into
Value: x has potential to directly develop into y iff x directly develops into y or x is capable of directly developing into y

Subject: has potential to directly develop into
Value: x has potential to directly develop into y iff x directly develops into y or x is capable of directly developing into y@en

Subject: causally upstream of
Value: p is causally upstream of q if and only if p precedes q and p and q are linked in a causal chain

Subject: immediately causally upstream of
Value: p is immediately causally upstream of q iff both (a) p immediately precedes q and (b) p is causally upstream of q. In addition, the output of p  must be an input of q.

Subject: causally upstream of or within
Value: p 'causally upstream or within' q iff (1) the end of p is before the end of q and (2) the execution of p exerts some causal influence over the outputs of q; i.e. if p was abolished or the outputs of p were to be modified, this would necessarily affect q.

Subject: causally downstream of or within
Value: inverse of causally upstream of or within

Subject: involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' regulates some p

Subject: involved in positive regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' positively regulates some p

Subject: involved in negative regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' negatively regulates some p

Subject: involved in or involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in or regulates p if and only if either (i) c is involved in p or (ii) c is involved in regulation of p

Subject: is active in
Value: c executes activity in d if and only if c enables p and p occurs_in d.  Assuming no action at a distance by gene products, if a gene product enables (is capable of) a process that occurs in some structure, it must have at least some part in that structure.

Subject: contributes to morphology of
composed primarily of
Value: x composed_primarily_of y if and only if more than half of the mass of x is made from y or units of the same type as y.

Subject: composed primarily of
Value: <x composed_primarily_of y iff: more than half of the mass of x is made from parts of y>

Subject: has part that occurs in
Value: p has part that occurs in c if and only if there exists some p1, such that p has_part p1, and p1 occurs in c.

Subject: existence starts during
Value: <x existence starts during y if and only if the time point at which x starts is after or equivalent to the time point at which y starts and before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: x existence starts during y iff (x) >= (y) & (x) <= (y).>

Subject: existence starts with
Value: <x starts ends with y if and only if the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x existence starts with y iff (x) = (y).>

Subject: existence overlaps
Value: <x existence overlaps y if and only if either (a) the start of x is part of y or (b) the end of x is part of y. Formally: x existence starts and ends during y iff ((x) >= (y) & (x) <= (y)) OR ((x) <= (y) & (x) >= (y))>

Subject: existence starts and ends during
Value: <x exists during y if and only if: 1) the time point at which x begins to exist is after or equal to the time point at which y begins and 2) the time point at which x ceases to exist is before or equal to the point at which y ends. Formally: x existence starts and ends during y iff (x) >= (y) & (x) <= (y) & (x) <= (y) & (x) >= (y)>

Subject: existence ends during
Value: <x existence ends during y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends and after or equivalent to the point at which y starts. Formally: x existence ends during y iff (x) <= (y) and (x) >= (y).>

Subject: existence ends with
Value: <x existence ends with y if and only if the time point at which x ends is equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: x existence ends with y iff (x) = (y).>

Subject: transformation of
Value: x transformation of y if x is the immediate transformation of y, or is linked to y through a chain of transformation relationships

Subject: immediate transformation of
Value: x immediate transformation of y iff x immediately succeeds y temporally at a time boundary t, and all of the matter present in x at t is present in y at t, and all the matter in y at t is present in x at t

Subject: existence starts during or after
Value: <x existence starts during or after y if and only if the time point at which x starts is after or equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x existence starts during or after y iff  (x) >=  (y).>

Subject: existence ends during or before
Value: x existence ends during or before y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends.

Subject: causal relation between processes
Value: p is causally related to q if and only if p or any part of p and q or any part of q are linked by a chain of events where each event pair is one of direct activation or direct inhibition. p may be upstream, downstream, part of or a container of q.

Subject: determined by
Value: s determined by f if and only if s is a type of system, and f is a material entity that is part of s, such that f exerts a strong causal influence on the functioning of s, and the removal of f would cause the collapse of s.

Subject: determined by part of
Value: s 'determined by part of' w if and only if there exists some f such that (1) s 'determined by' f and (2) f part_of w, or f=w.

Subject: has muscle antagonist
Value: m1 has_muscle_antagonist m2 iff m1 acts in opposition to m2, and m2 is responsible for returning the structure to its initial position.

Subject: has muscle antagonist
Value: m1 has_muscle_antagonist m2 iff m1 has_muscle_insertion s, m2 has_muscle_insection s, m1 acts in opposition to m2, and m2 is responsible for returning the structure to its initial position.

Subject: lumen of
Value: x lumen_of y iff x is the space or substance that is part of y and does not cross any of the inner membranes or boundaries of y that is maximal with respect to the volume of the convex hull.

Subject: luminal space of
Value: s is luminal space of x iff s is lumen_of x and s is an immaterial entity

Subject: is direct form of
Value: <relation p is the direct form of relation q iff p is a subPropertyOf q, p does not have the Transitive characteristic, q does have the Transitive characteristic, and for all x, y: x q y -> exists z1, z2, ..., zn such that x p z1 ... z2n y>

Subject: has part structure that is capable of
Value: s 'has part structure that is capable of' p if and only if there exists some part x such that s 'has part' x and x 'capable of' p

Subject: is_opposite_of
Value: x is the opposite of y if there exists some distance metric M, and there exists no z such as M(x,z) <= M(x,y) or M(y,z) <= M(y,x).

Subject: produces
Value: <a produces b if some process that occurs_in a has_output b, where a and b are material entities. Examples: hybridoma cell line produces monoclonal antibody reagent; chondroblast produces avascular GAG-rich matrix.>

Subject: produced_by
Value: a produced_by b iff some process that occurs_in b has_output a.

Subject: acts upstream of, positive effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, positive effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is positive

Subject: acts upstream of, negative effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, negative effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is negative

Subject: realized in response to
Value: r 'realized in response to' s iff, r is a realizable (e.g. a plant trait such as responsivity to drought), s is an environmental stimulus (a process), and s directly causes the realization of r.

Subject: islet of Langerhans
Value: the clusters of hormone-producing cells that are scattered throughout the pancreas

Subject: serous membrane
Value: multi-tissue structure that is comprised of a secretory epithelial layer (mesothelium) and a connective tissue layer.

Subject: urethra
Value: the fibromuscular tubular canal through which urine is discharged from the bladder to the exterior via the external urinary meatus; in males, the urethra is joined by the ejaculatory ducts and serves as a passageway for semen during ejaculation, as well as a canal for urine during voiding; in females, the urethra is shorter and emerges above the vaginal opening

Subject: trophoblast
Value: the mesectodermal cell layer arising from the trophectoderm that erodes the uterine mucosa and contributes to the formation of the placenta

Subject: post-embryonic stage
Value: stage succeeding embryo, including mature structure

Subject: cardiac neural crest
Value: portion of neural crest that develops from the dorsal neural tube. It overlaps the vagal neural crest and migrates to populate the pharyngeal arches 3, 4 and 6 (producing structures in the head) and to the heart, forming connective tissue that separates the great vessels of the heart. [Wikipedia]

Subject: lung connective tissue
Value: the connective tissue located between the respiratory (airway and alveolar) epithelium, the capillary endothelium and pleural mesothelium; it contains basement membrane composed of collagen, elastin, proteoglycans, and fibronectin

Subject: facial nucleus
Value: the group of motor neurons residing in the pons that innervate the muscles of facial expression

Subject: embryonic cloaca
Value: endoderm-lined chamber that develops as pouch-like dilation of the caudal end of the hindgut and receives the allantois ventrally and two mesonephric ducts laterally; caudally it ends blindly at the cloacal membrane formed by the union of proctodeal (anal pit) ectoderm and cloacal endoderm, with no intervening mesoderm[MP].

Subject: primitive urogenital sinus
Value: the ventral part of the cloaca remaining after septation of the rectum, which further develops into part of the bladder, part of the prostatic part of the male urethra and the urethra and vestibule in females

Subject: amnion
Value: the thin innermost layer of the extraembryonic membranes that contains the amniotic fluid; the membrane forms a closed sac in which the embryo and later, the fetus, is suspended and protected

Subject: parenchyma
Value: functional part of an organ in the body. This is in contrast to the stroma, which refers to the structural tissue of organs, being exactly, connective tissues.

Subject: cornea
Value: the transparent anterior portion of the fibrous coat of the eye that serves as the chief refractory structure

Subject: ovary
Value: the gonad of a female organism which contains germ cells

Subject: uterus
Value: the female muscular organ of gestation in which the developing embryo or fetus is nourished until birth

Subject: mammalian vulva
Value: external genital organs of the female mammal[WP].

Subject: circulatory system
Value: organ system that passes nutrients (such as amino acids and electrolytes), gases, hormones, blood cells, etc. to and from cells in the body to help fight diseases and help stabilize body temperature and pH to maintain homeostasis[WP].

Subject: rectum
Value: the terminal portion of the intestinal tube, terminating with the anus

Subject: cystic duct
Value: the tubular structure that conducts gall bladder contents from the gall bladder to the common bile duct

Subject: pyloric antrum
Value: the area at the bottom of the stomach on the caudal side of the pyloric canal that contains gastrin-producing G cells, which stimulate acid production, and the luminal pH-sensitive population of somatostatin-producing D cells

Subject: pylorus
Value: the stomach tissue region surrounding and controlling the distal outlet of the stomach, which opens into the duodenum

Subject: wall of stomach
Value: the layered structure that makes up the stomach, typiclly consists of a serous coat, a muscular coat, a mucous membrane, and other tissue layers in between

Subject: common bile duct
Value: the part of the biliary tree formed by the union of the cystic duct and the common hepatic duct

Subject: submucosa of stomach
Value: the fibrous connective tissue layer beneath the stomach mucosa

Subject: serosa of stomach
Value: the outermost layer of the stomach wall, consisting of layers of connective tissue continuous with the peritoneum

Subject: submucosa of small intestine
Value: submucosal tissue in the small intestines.

Subject: intestinal villus
Value: the tiny hair-like projections that protrude from the inside of the small intestine that contain blood vessels that capture digested nutrients that are absorbed through the intestinal wall; the villi increase the absorptive surface area of the small intestine by approximately 30-fold

Subject: urinary bladder
Value: distensible musculomembranous organ situated in the anterior part of the pelvic cavity in which urine collects before excretion[MP].

Subject: mucosa of urinary bladder
Value: the mucous membrane lining the urinary bladder

Subject: intralobular bile duct
Value: the tubules located between the bile canaliculi and interlobular bile ducts near the outer edge of a classic liver lobule

Subject: endometrium
Value: the glandular mucous membrane lining of the uterine cavity that is hormonally responsive during the estrous/menstrual cycle and during pregnancy

Subject: glans penis
Value: the conic expansion of the corpus spongiosum that forms the head of the penis

Subject: epididymis
Value: the elongated structure connected to the posterior surface of the testis that transports, stores, and matures spermatozoa between testis and vas deferens

Subject: thoracic aorta
Value: the part of the aorta that extends from the origin at the heart to the diaphragm, and from which arises numerous branches that supply oxygenated blood to the chest cage and the organs within the chest

Subject: occipital bone
Value: the bone at the lower, posterior part of the skull

Subject: temporal bone
Value: <the large, irregular bone located at the base and side of the skull; consists of three parts at birth: squamous, tympanic, and petrous>

Subject: geniculate ganglion
Value: the group of sensory neuron cell bodies associated with the facial nerve (seventh cranial nerve)

Subject: cranial ganglion
Value: the groups of nerve cell bodies associated with the twelve cranial nerves

Subject: anterior chamber of eyeball
Value: the space in the eye, filled with aqueous humor, and bounded anteriorly by the cornea and a small portion of the sclera and posteriorly by a small portion of the ciliary body, the iris, and part of the crystalline lens

Subject: uvea
Value: the pigmented middle of the three concentric layers that make up an eye, consisting of the iris, ciliary body and choroid[WP,edited].

Subject: iris
Value: the adjustable membrane, composed of the stroma and pigmented epithelium, located just in front of the crystalline lens within the eye

Subject: corneal epithelium
Value: the smooth stratified squamous epithelium that covers the outer surface of the cornea

Subject: ciliary body
Value: the thickened portion of the vascular tunic, which lies between the choroid and the iris, composed of ciliary muscle and ciliary processes

Subject: optic choroid
Value: vascular layer containing connective tissue, of the eye lying between the retina and the sclera. The choroid provides oxygen and nourishment to the outer layers of the retina. Along with the ciliary body and iris, the choroid forms the uveal tract[WP].

Subject: substantia propria of cornea
Value: the lamellated connective tissue of the cornea between the Bowman and Descemet membranes

Subject: spinal nerve
Value: the any of the paired peripheral nerves formed by the union of the dorsal and ventral spinal roots from each spinal cord segment[MP,modified]

Subject: anterior segment of eyeball
Value: any of the parts of the eye that lie in front of, or ventral to, the lens (inclusive)

Subject: posterior segment of eyeball
Value: any of the parts of the eye that lie in back of, or dorsal to, the lens (but not inclusive)

Subject: capsule of lens
Value: the elastic, clear, membrane-like structure, that is outer most layer of the lens

Subject: autonomic ganglion
Value: ganglion that has dendrites that form a junction between autonomic nerves originating from the central nervous system and autonomic nerves innervating their target organs in the periphery. There are two subtypes, sympathetic ganglion and parasympathetic ganglion.

Subject: spinal nerve plexus
Value: an intermingling of fiber fascicles from adjacent spinal nerves to form a network.

Subject: sweat gland
Value: any of the coil glands of the skin that secrete sweat

Subject: auricular cartilage
Value: cartilage of the pinna and much of the external ear canal.

Subject: epithelium of trachea
Value: the epithelial lining of the trachea which contains numerous ciliated cells

Subject: bile
Value: vital aqueous secretion of the liver that is formed by hepatocytes and modified down stream by absorptive and secretory properties of the bile duct epithelium.

Subject: placenta
Value: organ of metabolic interchange between fetus and mother, partly of embryonic origin and partly of maternal origin[GO]. The fetal portion of the placenta is known as the villous chorion. The maternal portion is known as the decidua basalis. The two portions are held together by anchoring villi that are anchored to the decidua basalis by the cytotrophoblastic shell.

Subject: kidney capsule
Value: the tough fibrous layer surrounding the kidney which is covered in a thick layer of perirenal adipose tissue that functions to provide some protection from trauma and damage

Subject: bronchus
Value: the upper conducting airways of the lung; these airways arise from the terminus of the trachea

Subject: bronchiole
Value: the conducting airway of the lungs found terminal to the bronchi; these structures contain neither cartilage nor mucous-secreting glands; the epithelium of the bronchioles becomes thinner with each branching

Subject: terminal bronchiole
Value: the last conducting structure of non-respiratory bronchioles; after this point, the airways have alveoli in their walls

Subject: myocardium of atrium
Value: the atrial part of middle layer of the heart, comprised of involuntary muscle

Subject: epicardium
Value: a region of the serous membrane that forms the innermost layer of the pericardium and the outer surface of the heart.

Subject: myocardium
Value: the middle layer of the heart, comprised mainly of striated cardiac muscle fibers

Subject: pes
Value: distal portion of the hind limb, including tarsal region, metatarsal region and digits.

Subject: manus
Value: distal segment of the fore limb, including carpal region, metacarpal region and digits.

Subject: pericardial sac
Value: a double-walled sac containing the heart and the roots of the great vessels.

Subject: clitoris
Value: the small, erectile body located at the anterior end of the vulva

Subject: gland
Value: an organ that functions as a secretory or excretory organ

Subject: cranial neural crest
Value: neural crest cells (NCCs) originating in the anterior part of the developing embryo and residing between the mid-diencephalon and the forming hindbrain; cranial NCCs migrate dorsolaterally to form the craniofacial mesenchyme that differentiates into various craniofacial cartilages and bones, cranial neurons, glia, and connective tissues of the face; these cells enter the pharyngeal pouches and arches where they give rise to thymic cells, bones of the middle ear and jaw (mandible), and the odontoblasts of the tooth primordia; like their counterparts in the trunk, cranial NCCs also contribute to the developing peripheral nervous system, along with the pigmented cell (i.e. melanocyte) lineage.

Subject: pharyngeal arch 4
Value: contributes to development of the cartilage of the larynx, laryngeal, pharyngeal, and soft palate muscles, superior parathyroid gland, and C-cells of the thymus

Subject: metanephric mesenchyme
Value: one of the two embryological structures that give rise to the kidney (the other is the ureteric bud). The metanephric blastema mostly develops into nephrons, but can also form parts of the collecting duct system.[WP]. Metanephric mesenchyme is the tissue made up of loosely connected mesenchymal cells in the metanephros[GO]

Subject: smooth muscle of eye
Value: <any of the striated muscles that move the eye and include: superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, lateral rectus, superior oblique, inferior oblique, retractor bulbi>

Subject: trachea cartilage
Value: the ring-shaped cartilaginous structures that support the trachea

Subject: Mullerian duct
Value: paired ducts of the embryo that run down the lateral sides of the urogenital ridge and terminate at the mullerian eminence in the primitive urogenital sinus. In the female, they will develop to form the fallopian tubes, uterus, and the upper portion of the vagina; in the male, they are lost. These ducts are made of tissue of mesodermal origin[WP]. develops either by lengthwise splitting of the archinephric duct (in chondrichthyans and some amphibians) or by a elongated invagination of the coelomic epithelium (other vertebrates) In males, the oviducts regress. The cranial end of the oviduct maintains an opening into the coelom (which primitively may have been the anteriormost coelomic funnels connecting the nephrocoel with the coelom). This opening is the ostium tubae[USM].

Subject: pancreas primordium
Value: embryonic structure that develops into pancreatic bud.

Subject: dorsal pancreatic bud
Value: pancreatic bud that gives rise to the accessory pancreatic duct.

Subject: ventral pancreatic bud
Value: pancreatic bud that gives rise to the major pancreatic duct.

Subject: tympanic cavity
Value: small cavity surrounding the bones of the middle ear.

Subject: aorta smooth muscle tissue
Value: the nonstriated, involuntary muscle tissue located in the wall of the aorta

Subject: kidney pelvis smooth muscle
Value: the smooth muscle tissue surrounding the urothelium of the kidney pelvis

Subject: blood vessel smooth muscle
Value: smooth muscle found within, and composing the majority of the wall of blood vessels.

Subject: trophectoderm
Value: outermost layer of cells in the blastodermic vesicle, which will develop into the trophoblast layer and then contact the endometrium and take part in establishing the embryo's means of nutrition

Subject: apical ectodermal ridge
Value: multilayered ectodermal region at the distal tip of a limb or fin bud necessary for the proper development of the underlying mesenchyme[MP,modified]. Along with the zone of polarizing activity, it is a crucial organizing region during limb development[WP].

Subject: vitelline blood vessel
Value: blood vessel that is connected to the yolk sac.

Subject: vitelline vasculature
Value: vascular network that is connected to the yolk sac.

Subject: epididymis epithelium
Value: the layer of secretory cells which lines the epididymis

Subject: liver lobule
Value: the polygonal structure of the liver that consists of hepatocytes radiating outward from a hepatic vein

Subject: aorta tunica adventitia
Value: the outermost layer of the aorta wall, containing connective tissue and collagen and elastic fibers

Subject: bulbus cordis
Value: a transient fetal dilation of the distal (or cranial) heart tube located where the arterial trunk joins the ventral roots of the aortic arches

Subject: dermal skeletal element
Value: dermis-derived entity that is made of skeletal tissue.

Subject: respiratory system mucosa
Value: the mucous membrane lining the respiratory tract

Subject: respiratory tract epithelium
Value: the pseudostratified ciliated epithelium that lines much of the conducting portion of the airway, including part of the nasal cavity and larynx, the trachea, and bronchi

Subject: nephron tubule epithelium
Value: the cellular avascular layer of the renal tubule luminar surfaces

Subject: seminiferous tubule epithelium
Value: the stratified epithelial lining of the seminiferous tubules, consisting of the developing spermatozoa and the supporting Sertoli cells, which are tall, columnar type cells that line the tubule

Subject: kidney epithelium
Value: the cellular avascular layer of the kidney luminar surfaces

Subject: aorta endothelium
Value: the thin layer of flat cells that line the aorta and form a barrier between circulating blood in the lumen and the rest of the vessel wall

Subject: sphincter of hepatopancreatic ampulla
Value: muscular valve that controls the flow of digestive juices (bile and pancreatic juice) through the ampulla of Vater into the second part of the duodenum. Relaxed by the hormone Cholecystokinin (CCK) via vasoactive intestinal polypeptide (VIP).[WP].

Subject: gonadal ridge
Value: the elevation of thickened mesothelium and underlying mesenchyme found on the ventromedial border of the embryonic mesonephros in which the primordial germ cells become embedded, establishing it as the primordium of the testis or ovary

Subject: ovary sex cord
Value: structures that develop from sex cords in the female. After further development they become the ovarian follicles.

Subject: vagus X ganglion
Value: the group of sensory neuron cell bodies associated with the vagus nerve

Subject: vitelline vein
Value: the paired veins that carry blood from the yolk sac back to the embryo

Subject: mandibular prominence
Value: the paired ventral prominences formed by bifurcation of the first pharyngeal arches in the embryo; the two prominences unite ventrally and fuse to form the mandible and lower lip

Subject: undifferentiated genital tubercle
Value: the embryonic anlage of the external genitalia, which emerges as paired swellings ventral to the cloacal membrane, is proposed to be derived from all three germ layers, and gives rise to the penis, clitoris, scrotum, labia, and foreskin

Subject: otic pit
Value: the pair of depressions of thickened otic placode epithelium, that further develops into the otic vesicles

Subject: os penis
Value: the unique bone located in the glans penis of most mammals except humans; it is used for copulation and varies in size and shape by species

Subject: corneo-scleral junction
Value: the edge of the cornea where it joins the sclera; the limbus is a common site for the occurrence of corneal epithelial neoplasm

Subject: embryonic footplate
Value: the distal elements of the developing limb of vertebrates that will give rise to the pes (foot)

Subject: embryonic handplate
Value: the distal elements of the developing limb of vertebrates that will give rise to the manus (hand)

Subject: stomach glandular region mucosa
Value: stomach mucosa that is lined with glandular epithelium and part of a stomach glandular region.

Subject: inner ear epithelium
Value: the epithelial cell layer containing the sensory hair cells and their associated sensory nerve terminals

Subject: hermaphroditic organism
Value: multicellular organism that can produce both male and female gametes.

Subject: pigment epithelium of eye
Value: epithelial layer of the retina, ciliary body, or iris composed of cells containing pigment granules.

Subject: uriniferous tubule
Value: functional unit of the kidney that forms urine, consisting of two parts, the nephron and the collecting tubule.

Subject: kidney field
Value: region of the embryo into the area in which the kidney rudiment will develop.

Subject: erectile tissue
Value: with numerous vascular spaces that may become engorged with blood

Subject: nephrogenic zone
Value: outer portion of the renal cortex. Site of formation of medullary and cortical elements.

Subject: neuroendocrine gland
Value: any of the organized aggregations of cells that function as secretory or excretory organs and that release hormones in response to neural stimuli

Subject: male urethral gland
Value: any of the numerous small mucous-secreting glands located in the wall of the penile urethra

Subject: pair of dorsal aortae
Value: the paired arterial structures of the embryo that supplies each developing somite via efferent segmental arteries; the dorsal aortae articulate with the umbilical arteries, which return mixed blood to the villi of the chorion for reoxygenation

Subject: yolk sac blood island
Value: masses of developing blood cells attached to endothelium in the yolk sac

Subject: umbilical cord blood
Value: blood that remains in the placenta and in the attached umbilical cord after childbirth[WP].

Subject: urinary bladder vasculature
Value: network of tubes that carries blood through the distensible musculomembranous organ that serves to collect and store urine excreted by the kidneys[MP]

Subject: urethral meatus
Value: external opening or orifice of the urethra through which urine and seminal fluid (in males only) leave the body; in males the meatus presents as a vertical slit normally positioned at the tip of glans penis; in females the meatus is located between the clitoris and the vagina in the vulvular vestibule of the female genitalia[MP].

Subject: internal urethral orifice
Value: the usually crescent-shaped opening of the urinary bladder into the urethra, placed at the anteroinferior angle (apex) of the urinary bladder trigone

Subject: ovarian cortex
Value: the layer of the ovarian stroma lying immediately beneath the tunica albuginea, composed of connective tissue cells and fibers, among which are scattered primary and secondary (antral) follicles in various stages of development; the cortex varies in thickness according to the age of the individual, becoming thinner with advancing years; included in the follicles are the cumulus oophorus, membrana granulosa (and the granulosa cells inside it), corona radiata, zona pellucida, and primary oocyte; the zona pellucida, theca of follicle, antrum and liquor folliculi are also contained in the follicle; also in the cortex is the corpus luteum derived from the follicles.

Subject: choledocho-duodenal junction
Value: hat part of the duodenal wall traversed by the ductus choledochus, ductus pancreaticus, and ampulla.

Subject: auditory system
Value: is the sensory system for the sense of hearing.

Subject: cavity of left atrium
Value: luminal space of the left atrium of the heart.

Subject: cavity of left ventricle
Value: luminal space of the left ventricle of the heart.

Subject: cavity of right atrium
Value: luminal space of the right atrium of the heart.

Subject: phlegm
Value: mucus produced in the respiratory tract.

Subject: prechordal mesoderm
Value: the area of axial mesoderm that develops into the prechordal plate

Subject: wall of heart
Value: wall of organ which has as its parts the endocardium, myocardium , epicardium, and the cardiac septum, surrounded by the pericardial sac proper and is continuous with the walls of the systemic and pulmonary arterial and venous trees.

Subject: pharyngeal arch number
Value: x pharyngeal_arch_number N if and only if (i) x is a pharyngeal arch, and (ii) x is ancestrally pharyngeal arch number N in a series of pharyngeal arches repeated along a antero-posterior axis, with arch_number 1 being the mandibular arch.

Subject: decreased_in_magnitude_relative_to
Value: q1 decreased_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) < magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: different_in_magnitude_relative_to
Value: q1 different_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) NOT =~ magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: increased_in_magnitude_relative_to
Value: q1 increased_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) > magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: reciprocal_of
Value: <q1 reciprocal_of q2 if and only if : q1 and q2 are relational qualities and a phenotype e q1 e2 mutually implies a phenotype e2 q2 e.>

Subject: anteriorly connected to
Value: x anteriorly_connected_to y iff the anterior part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x posterior_to y.

Subject: conduit for
Value: x is a conduit for y iff y passes through the lumen of x.

Subject: distally connected to
Value: x distally_connected_to y iff the distal part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x proximal_to y.

Subject: indirectly_supplies
Value: a indirectly_supplies s iff a has a branch and the branch supplies or indirectly supplies s

Subject: posteriorly connected to
Value: x posteriorly_connected_to y iff the posterior part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x anterior_to y.

Subject: proximally connected to
Value: x proximally_connected_to y iff the proximal part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x distal_to y.

Subject: Earth
Value: third planet from the Sun in the Solar System

Subject: Suni
Value: \"Suni, or Jalca, is one of the eight Natural Regions of Peru. It is located in the Andes at an altitude between 3,500 and 4,000 metres above sea level. Suni has a dry and cold weather and there are many glacial valleys. The flora includes gramineous plants and shrubs such as the taya-taya (Caesalpinia spinosa), the quishuar (Buddleja coriacea), and the cantuta (Cantua buxifolia) which was considered sacred by the Incas. Even though it is hard for plants to grow because of the weather, people are able to cultivate such crops as quinoa, qaiwa, broad beans and ulluku (Ullucus tuberosus). The main fauna is the guinea pig and, among numerous other highland birds, the Chiguanco thrush.\"
